<item>
            <title>[LUDOC-151] least qunit is 1K but not 1000</title>
                <link>https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LUDOC-151</link>
                <project id="10070" key="LUDOC">Lustre Documentation</project>
                    <description>&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;To reduce quota requests, quota space is initially allocated to QSDs in very large chunks. How much unused quota space can be hold by a target is controlled by the qunit size. When quota space &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;for&lt;/span&gt; a given ID is close to exhaustion on the QMT, the qunit size is reduced and QSDs are notified of the &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;new&lt;/span&gt; qunit size value via a glimpse callback. Slaves are then responsible &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;for&lt;/span&gt; releasing quota space above the &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;new&lt;/span&gt; qunit value. The qunit size isn&apos;t shrunk indefinitely and there is a minimal value of 1MB &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;for&lt;/span&gt; blocks and 1,000 &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;for&lt;/span&gt; inodes. This means that the quota space rebalancing process will stop when &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;this&lt;/span&gt; mininum value is reached. As a result, quota exceeded can be returned &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;while&lt;/span&gt; many slaves still have 1MB or 1,000 inodes of spare quota space.
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The &apos;1,000&apos; should be replaced with 1,024 since the least inode qunit is 1K but not 1000.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
